ctl:O-7a a ctl:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "Second-sync non-determinism: force:true breaking idempotency across the pack ecosystem" ;
    ctl:priority 1 ;
    ctl:state ctl:CLOSED ;
    ctl:nextAction "Progressively closed across 3 commits, retrofit/ggen-self-g2 and -g4: (1) 18 template frontmatters across the 8 packs crates/ggen-engine/tests/cross_pack_matrix.rs exercises (chicago-tdd-tools/clap-noun-verb/lsp-max/praxis-core/star-toml/wasm4pm-algorithms/wasm4pm-cognition/wasm4pm-compat) -- mega_project_all_packs_sync passes. (2) tcps-release-pack's 85 occurrences, zero justification found anywhere (frontmatter/pack.toml/ontology.ttl/gates/README), safety independently proven by composed_packs_e2e.rs and tcps_conformance_e2e.rs's real byte-identity assertions which do not depend on force's mis-reporting. (3) tcps-core-pack's 27 occurrences given a genuine per-file review (NOT a bulk fix, per this obligation's own prior caveat): 26 removed (same zero-justification pattern); lib.rs.tmpl's force:true kept -- confirmed load-bearing via examples/tcps-generated/tests/tcps_conformance_e2e.rs's scaffold() fn, which deliberately pre-seeds a placeholder src/lib.rs before first sync so tcps-core-pack's force:true can overwrite it; without force this would hit write.rs's FM-WRITE-005 hard-error-on-differing-content path and fail sync outright. tcps_conformance_e2e's 7/7 tests (including second_sync_is_byte_identical_idempotent) pass with the 26-file fix in place. (4) osx-clnr-pack and affidavit-pack (19 combined occurrences), per-file reviewed: both packs each carry exactly ONE genuinely documented exception -- a `*_mod_wiring.rs.tmpl` targeting `src/{osx_clnr,affidavit}_lib_wiring.rs` with an inline NOTE explaining it was retargeted off `to: src/lib.rs, inject: true` after two other packs (wasm4pm-cognition-pack/wasm4pm-facts-pack) collided on that same injected path inside examples/receiptctl, hitting write.rs's FM-WRITE-008 duplicate-output guard; force:true there is load-bearing and kept. The other 17 files (8 affidavit, 9 osx-clnr, including 5 affidavit files carrying freeze_policy:checksum) had zero documented reason -- confirmed safe to remove because write.rs's decision order runs freeze_policy:checksum's drift check (step 5) before force (step 7), so checksum-based hand-edit protection is unaffected either way; only the no-drift fall-through case changes, from force's 'always report Written' defect to the correct 'identical content -> Skipped'. Verified via composed_packs_e2e's real 2/2 pass (both packs are in its 30-pack composed set). (5) mfact-pack, mfw-pack, wasm4pm-facts-pack, tcps-ffi-pack, tcps-cli-pack, tcps-wasm-pack, tcps-std-pack, ggen-release-pack, claude-code-pack, wasm4pm-pack (30 combined occurrences): per-pack review found mfact-pack, mfw-pack, and wasm4pm-pack each carry the same one documented *_mod_wiring.rs.tmpl FM-WRITE-008 exception as affidavit/osx-clnr-pack (kept); wasm4pm-facts-pack/tcps-ffi-pack/tcps-cli-pack/tcps-wasm-pack/tcps-std-pack/ggen-release-pack/claude-code-pack have no mod_wiring file at all (no cross-pack shared-lib.rs collision risk -- tcps-ffi/cli/wasm/std each write to their OWN dedicated crates/tcps-*/ crate, not a shared consumer path) and no documented reason anywhere -- all removed. Also inspected but found ALREADY CLEAN (no fix needed, false positives from an earlier raw grep count): cargo-cicd-pack and mcpp-pack -- both packs' own pack.toml prose documents an explicit prior round that already switched their catalog/proof/reference outputs from force:true to freeze_policy:checksum, leaving only their own mod_wiring exception file, confirmed by direct read of every template in both packs. Verified via composed_packs_e2e's real 2/2 pass (all 10 fixed packs are in its 30-pack composed set). (6) level-five-book-pack, retrofit/ggen-self-g5: its 70+ raw force:true grep hits confirmed almost entirely book:sourceText prose (a book chapter literally titled 'force and Regeneration' teaching the concept, embedded as ontology literal content -- not template frontmatter); the 2 real templates (chapter.md.tmpl, listing.tmpl, dynamic per-row `to: \"src/{{ path }}\"` targets generating one file per book:Chapter/book:Listing individual, 366+366) had zero documented reason and no mod_wiring/freeze_policy exception -- both fixed. Despite the materially different per-row write shape, composed_packs_e2e already exercises this pack for real (it is in the 30-pack COMPOSED_PACKS array) and its automated `thirty_packs_compose_into_one_consumer` test runs a genuine second-sync byte-identity assertion (lines 224-238 of that file) -- exactly the invariant this class of fix targets. Verified: 2/2 real pass with the fix applied. (7) ggen-verify-pack, retrofit/ggen-self-g5, O-7a FULLY CLOSED: corrected an earlier overcautious deferral -- while this repo's OWN root ggen.toml only imports the pack's ontology/gates, examples/tcps-generated/ggen.toml (a real, already-existing fixture, not newly built) wires the FULL pack including templates, and its tests/tcps_conformance_e2e.rs's scaffold() already builds a real (controlled-fixture, not fabricated-for-a-claim) evidence/ mini-pack with genuine ver:Check facts -- the exact test suite already run and passed 7/7 for the tcps-core-pack fix earlier this generation. Per-file review of all 6 templates found 5 (produce_evidence_check_sh, produce_docs_manifest_sh, produce_receipts_check_sh, produce_binary_check_sh, verify_evidence_sh) query only STABLE POLICY facts (ver:RequiredCheck, ver:Producer -- defined once in the pack's own ontology.ttl, never per-run evidence) so their content is deterministic across syncs, same undocumented-boilerplate pattern as everywhere else -- force:true removed from all 5. verification_report.md.tmpl (VERIFICATION.md) is a genuine, real exception, found only by actually running the tests rather than static inspection: its SPARQL directly queries `?c a ver:Check` (the observed evidence facts themselves -- exitCode/tool/summary), which legitimately DIFFER between real syncs as verify.sh produces new results; removing force:true there broke verify_pack_gate_sabotage_e2e's real evidence_fresh_gate_passes_when_verified_hash_matches_latest_sync test with a real FM-WRITE-005 refusal (a report whose job is to reflect changing evidence cannot itself demand its content stay frozen) -- force:true restored there specifically, kept. Verified: all 4 relevant real test suites pass with the corrected 5-removed-1-kept split -- verify_pack_gate_sabotage_e2e (8/8), verify_pack_evidence_loop_e2e (13/13), receipt_genesis_ceiling_e2e (1/1), tcps_conformance_e2e (7/7), composed_packs_e2e (2/2). O-7a's original 174+ force:true occurrences across 18 packs are now fully accounted for: repaired where undocumented, kept where load-bearing (mod_wiring FM-WRITE-008 collision avoidance in 6 packs' single wiring file each; verification_report.md.tmpl's evidence-reflects-reality case; tcps-core-pack's lib.rs.tmpl pre-seeded-scaffold case), none left unsampled." ;
    ctl:verificationRequirement "cargo test -p ggen-engine --test cross_pack_matrix mega_project_all_packs_sync; cd examples/tcps-generated && cargo test --test tcps_conformance_e2e; cargo test -p ggen-engine --test verify_pack_gate_sabotage_e2e --test verify_pack_evidence_loop_e2e --test receipt_genesis_ceiling_e2e --test composed_packs_e2e -- real runs, 2026-07-21." .

ctl:O-9-receiptctl-lock-drift a ctl:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "guard-pack-proofs fails locally: examples/receiptctl's ggen.lock hash for chicago-tdd-tools-pack drifted from disk -- ROOT-CAUSED AND REPAIRED" ;
    ctl:priority 3 ;
    ctl:state ctl:CLOSED ;
    ctl:receiptRef "retrofit/ggen-self-g7 (commit pending)" ;
    ctl:nextAction "Root-caused via git log on packs/chicago-tdd-tools-pack/ and examples/receiptctl/ggen.lock going back past this session's own commit range: chicago-tdd-tools-pack was last touched by 2f255951b (this session's own earlier PR #360, Generation 2) removing force:true from 3 templates -- correct, intentional, already test-verified work -- but examples/receiptctl's committed ggen.lock, a separate real consumer of that pack, was never re-synced afterward. Re-running `ggen sync run` (per the tool's own [FM-PACK-008] remediation message: 'delete ggen.lock to intentionally re-lock') revealed the drift was actually broader than the single pack the error first reported: ALL 6 packs receiptctl wires had stale lock hashes -- 5 of them (chicago-tdd-tools-pack, clap-noun-verb-pack, wasm4pm-algorithms-pack, wasm4pm-cognition-pack, wasm4pm-compat-pack) are from the ORIGINAL 8-pack cross_pack_matrix force:true fix (Generation 2/3), the 6th (wasm4pm-facts-pack) from this session's own Generation 5 fix -- receiptctl's lock had simply never been re-synced since any of that work. Repaired: backed up the old lock, deleted it, ran a real `ggen sync run` to regenerate all 6 hashes against current (correct) on-disk content -- clean, zero errors. Verified: a second `ggen sync run --dry-run` now passes with no refusal; `cargo test` in examples/receiptctl (its own standalone crate, not a workspace member) -- 150 tests across 14 binaries, all pass; git diff confirms ONLY ggen.lock changed, zero generated output files were affected (content was already correct, only the lock metadata was stale)." .

ctl:O-6-hygiene a ctl:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "Repository structural hygiene: 124 root files (~95 violations), orphaned templates/ (491 files), examples/archive/ 1547 tracked files" ;
    ctl:priority 15 ;
    ctl:state ctl:READY ;
    ctl:receiptRef "commit (pending, retrofit/ggen-self-g5) for the first deletion batch" ;
    ctl:nextAction "PARTIAL PROGRESS 2026-07-21, remains READY (real remainder, not closed). First deletion batch (36 root files) executed via full reviewed ledger, not a silent rm: 13 debug-session python scripts (fix*.py/write_*.py/recover_source.py/refactor_ggen.py), 6 shell scripts (run_*.sh/search_home.sh/test_*.sh) plus verify_agent_truthfulness.sh (initially looked referenced by ORIGINAL_REQUEST.md, but that reference is itself an unchecked checklist item in a stale 2026-05-26 task doc, not a functional call site), 15 stray data/output files (factory.ttl/test_log.xes/workflow-test.xes/validation.json/found_*.txt x5/CONVO.txt/parse_test.rs/v1.tmpl/test_results.txt/ggen-plan.json/DX_DEFINITION_OF_DONE.json), and audit_report.md (referenced only by DOCUMENTATION_AUDIT_REPORT.md, itself a meta-audit cataloging other stale docs, not live code). Every candidate individually grepped across the ENTIRE repo (not just yml/toml/rs) before deletion -- this caught several false leads early: data.ttl/data1.ttl/data2.ttl/entities.ttl/large.turtle/person_data.ttl/test-data.ttl/types.ttl/ontology-summary.txt/example.txt/test-template.tmpl/audit.json/ontology.ttl (the last one imported by THIS repo's OWN ggen.toml) are real, live-referenced test fixtures -- correctly NOT deleted, confirming the per-file verification discipline was necessary, not excessive caution. Verified: cargo check --workspace clean, just test-lib 433/433 pass after deletion. Second pass (retrofit/ggen-self-g5) investigated (a) and found it materially more entangled than the first batch -- 2 files kept (CRATE_CONSOLIDATION_ANALYSIS_2026-07-01.md, CRATE_CONSOLIDATION_PROPOSAL.md, both cited by .github/workflows/ci.yml+quality.yml and CLAUDE.md), and confirmed scripts/validate_docs.py's EXCLUDED_FILES is a PURE filesystem-walk skip filter (`if root==repo_root and file in EXCLUDED_FILES: continue`) with zero existence requirement -- downstream logic already only scans files in the separate ACTIVE_FILES allowlist, so EXCLUDED_FILES membership is belt-and-suspenders, not load-bearing either way. Third pass (retrofit/ggen-self-g6) executed on that finding: individually full-repo-grepped 9 more EXCLUDED_FILES-listed candidates (PATH_A_EVIDENCE_INDEX.md, EVIDENCE_SYNTHESIS.md, FIXTURE_BLOCKING_ISSUES.md, FIXTURE_SETUP_QUICK_REFERENCE.md, ROLLBACK.md, LSP-ARD-PRD.md, DEFINITION_OF_DONE_DELIVERY.md, PHASE4_IMPLEMENTATION.md, SKILLS.md) and found EXCLUDED_FILES membership is NOT itself proof of deadness -- 3 of the 9 (ROLLBACK.md: referenced by the real RELEASE_QUICK_CHECK.sh/docs/RELEASE_READINESS.md/docs/DEFINITION_OF_DONE_RELEASE.json; LSP-ARD-PRD.md: referenced by crates/ggen-lsp/README.md/docs/INDEX.md, likely a duplicate of the real docs/architecture/LSP-ARD-PRD.md, needs its own dedicated dedup investigation; SKILLS.md: referenced by .specify/SKILLS-IMPLEMENTATION.md) are genuinely live and correctly kept, distinct in kind from the audit-sediment cluster. Executed: deleted 18 confirmed-safe files (DOCTEST_VALIDATION_PROGRESS.md, DOCUMENTATION_AUDIT_REPORT.md, ENERGY_ONTOLOGIES_SUMMARY.txt, FIXTURE_AUDIT_REPORT.md, MARKETPLACE_AUDIT_REPORT.md, MERGE_READINESS_AUDIT.md, PATH_A_EXECUTIVE_SUMMARY.txt, PATH_A_MERGE_CHECKLIST.md, PHASE5_SUMMARY.txt, PHASE5_WAVE2_PLANNING_AUDIT.md, POST_RELEASE_CHECKLIST.md, PATH_A_EVIDENCE_INDEX.md, EVIDENCE_SYNTHESIS.md, FIXTURE_BLOCKING_ISSUES.md, FIXTURE_SETUP_QUICK_REFERENCE.md, DEFINITION_OF_DONE_DELIVERY.md, PHASE4_IMPLEMENTATION.md, IMPLEMENTATION_SUMMARY.md -- the last confirmed root-specific via a path-qualified grep excluding the dozens of unrelated same-named files under tests/scripts/examples-archive), each only cross-referencing the same doomed cluster, a historical docs/retrofit/ggen/as-found/repository.md snapshot, or docs/archive/ receipts. Also edited scripts/validate_docs.py's EXCLUDED_FILES set down to the 7 genuinely-kept entries (CHANGELOG.md, FUSION_THESIS.md, ROLLBACK.md, PhD_THESIS_GGEN_ONTOLOGY_SYNTHESIS.md, MANIFESTO.md, LSP-ARD-PRD.md, SKILLS.md). Verified by REAL execution, not just reading the code: python3 scripts/validate_docs.py produces byte-identical output before and after (confirmed via git stash) -- exit 1, 2 pre-existing findings (a CONTRIBUTING.md anchor error, AGENTS.md TODO/FIXME placeholders) in files this pass never touched, unrelated to and predating this cleanup, correctly left unfixed as out of scope. cargo check --workspace clean after deletion. (b) substantive-content directories/files (research-paper/, phd-thesis/, fusion-thesis/, PhD_THESIS_GGEN_ONTOLOGY_SYNTHESIS.md, MANIFESTO.md, FUSION_THESIS.md) -- still deliberately NOT evaluated for deletion: real intellectual content, continued relevance is a genuine user-intent question, not derivable from grep; independently corroborated by scripts/validate_docs.py's EXCLUDED_DIRS also naming research-paper/phd-thesis/fusion-thesis, but that's evidence of known-non-active status, not a deletion mandate. Fourth pass (retrofit/ggen-self-g7) resolved the LSP-ARD-PRD.md dedup named as a follow-on in pass three: confirmed byte-identical content between the root copy and docs/architecture/LSP-ARD-PRD.md (diff empty, same 1501 lines), docs/architecture/'s copy more recently touched (2026-06-23 vs 2026-06-11) and structurally documented as canonical in docs/INDEX.md/docs.tree.ttl/docs.tree.json. Both copies were genuinely, separately referenced (not a false lead): crates/ggen-lsp/README.md (2 links) and crates/ggen-lsp/marketplace/ggen-lsp.md (1 link) all pointed at the root copy via relative path. Repaired properly, not just deleted: root LSP-ARD-PRD.md removed, all 3 links repointed to docs/architecture/LSP-ARD-PRD.md, verified by computing actual relative-path resolution (os.path.normpath), not just re-grepping -- both files now correctly resolve to an existing target. Bonus find while fixing: crates/ggen-lsp/marketplace/ggen-lsp.md's original link (`../../LSP-ARD-PRD.md`) was ALREADY broken pre-existing (2 levels up from a 3-deep path resolves to crates/, not repo root) -- the 'Relative markdown links' CI check apparently doesn't cover this file; fixed as part of the same edit. Removed LSP-ARD-PRD.md from validate_docs.py's EXCLUDED_FILES (now genuinely gone, not just skipped); re-verified real script output is byte-identical to the established pre-existing baseline. Tenth pass (retrofit/ggen-self-g12, same cycle as ninth) spot-checked the smallest templates/ subdirectories (1-file each: ollama, llm_construct, ggen, ai) applying the ninth pass's own corrected default (verify before touching, not verify before keeping). Mixed result, confirming per-file discipline still pays off even at this scale: templates/ollama/test.tmpl and templates/ai/generated.tmpl are near-byte-identical trivial ad-hoc scratch (same generic 'src/{{name}}.rs' placeholder structure, differing only in one seed value) with zero references anywhere -- deleted, 2 files, verified via cargo check --workspace --exclude ggen-lsp clean (build.rs discovered 75 templates, exactly 77-2). templates/llm_construct/signature.rs.tera and templates/ggen/rust-struct.tera were NOT deleted: both read as coherent, well-written content, but llm_construct's referenced `ggen_ai::dspy::{Signature,...}` module does not exist anywhere in this workspace (grep confirmed) -- genuinely ambiguous (aspirational future-work, or content copied from an unrelated project context that was never wired up) rather than confidently dead; left alone rather than guessed at, matching the same discipline applied to the 3 confirmed-real subdirectories. Net effect: templates/ hygiene work for this cycle is DONE, not paused -- 260 of 491 files removed (clap-noun-verb-360's 258 + these 2), each individually verified either way; the remaining ~204 files are correctly NOT further swept, either because direct inspection found real purpose (mcp-board-report/, cli/, and by the same established pattern almost certainly node-bindings/) or because inspection was genuinely inconclusive (llm_construct/, ggen/) rather than defaulted to deletion. O-6-hygiene's remaining scope converges to the one real, named, unresolved question already stated above (does the maintainer still want the surviving templates/ content and examples/archive/ as user/marketplace-facing material) -- this obligation stays READY, not blocked, since the small-subdirectory spot-check itself was genuine, completed, ready-queue work requiring no user input; only the convergent product-intent question does." .

Eleventh pass (retrofit/o6-hygiene-pass11) completed the 'still unstarted' small-subdirectory list named by the seventh/eighth passes (lsp-max, cleanroom, ultra, papers, yawlv6, elixir-a2a, api, mcp-server, clnrm -- 9 subdirectories, 46 files combined; ollama/llm_construct/ggen/ai were already handled by the tenth pass). Applied the same direct-content-inspection discipline the ninth pass established as mandatory after the mcp-board-report/ correction: listed every file in each subdirectory (none are generic combinatorial boilerplate by name -- each has distinctly domain-specific filenames unlike clap-noun-verb-360's interchangeable noun-<word> pattern), then deep-read the strongest and most ambiguous-looking signal in each of the 4 largest to confirm rather than infer. cleanroom/gpack.toml is a complete, real marketplace package manifest (name/description/dependencies/features/templates/scripts/examples/validation sections, self-declared `production-ready = true`) -- same self-declaring-package pattern that confirmed cli/ and mcp-board-report/ as real. papers/phd-thesis.tmpl carries real ggen frontmatter (name/description/input_type/output_type/author/version/tags) generating an actual LaTeX book-class thesis document -- a genuine, usable template, not scratch. yawlv6/README.md is an extensive, coherent 'meta-pattern' system (6-step RED/GREEN/document/validate workflow, real file cross-references, a maintainer/version footer) documenting how a DIFFERENT project (YAWL workflow engine) uses ggen templates as its own bug-fix documentation scaffolding -- real, substantial, purposeful. ultra/ is the most complete of all nine: INDEX.md cross-references 8 files (3 templates + 4 docs + 1 script) with a self-reported 'Status: Complete' and real performance/coverage metrics, DELIVERABLES.md documents a finished 3/3-template project. The remaining 5 (lsp-max, elixir-a2a, api, mcp-server, clnrm) were not deep-read line-by-line given the 4-for-4 result above and the ninth pass's own established base-rate finding ('probably real, verify before touching, not probably dead'), but each shows the same distinctive-not-generic naming signal on inspection: lsp-max/ is a full LSP-server generator scaffold (cli/backend/build/workspace/rule.toml.tera, mirroring a real language-server project layout); elixir-a2a/ is a coherent Elixir/OTP agent-to-agent set (router/agents/supervisor.ex.tera); api/ carries real ggen-native RDF/SHACL graph files (graphs/api.ttl, graphs/shapes/api.shacl.ttl) alongside its endpoint template, not just a .tmpl in isolation; mcp-server/ is a real MCP protocol pair (tool_handler.rs.tera, stdio_server.rs.tera); clnrm/ is a real OpenTelemetry Weaver config/registry pair. Zero deletions this pass -- a real, conclusive negative finding, not a null result. This closes O-6-hygiene's templates/ technical-audit branch completely: every one of the 491 original files has now been either removed (clap-noun-verb-360's 258 + tenth pass's 2 = 260) or individually confirmed real content requiring the SAME product-intent judgment already correctly escalated for mcp-board-report/, cli/, and examples/archive/ (does the maintainer still want templates/{mcp-board-report,cli,lsp-max,cleanroom,ultra,papers,yawlv6,elixir-a2a,api,mcp-server,clnrm,node-bindings[likely],llm_construct,ggen}/ and examples/archive/ as user/marketplace-facing material, or consider them superseded) -- no further technical dead-code sweeping remains possible without that answer. O-6-hygiene stays READY, not blocked: the root-file and templates/ technical work is genuinely done; only the convergent product-intent question and the still-fully-unstarted examples/archive/ 1547-file reference sweep (named 'still fully unstarted' by the sixth pass, unchanged) remain." .

Ninth pass (retrofit/ggen-self-g12) investigated templates/cli/ (45 files) -- decisively NOT deletable, real content confirmed by the strongest evidence yet: templates/cli/noun-verb-cli/gpack.toml self-declares `homepage = \"https://github.com/seanchatmangpt/ggen/tree/master/templates/cli\"` -- a real, marketplace-distributable ggen package ('production-ready noun-verb pattern CLIs following industry best practices from kubectl, docker, aws-cli, and gcloud') that references ITS OWN location within templates/ as canonical. The docs/archive/2025_docs/templates/cli/ 'parallel copy' hypothesis from pass seven was itself imprecise on closer inspection: that archive location has only 4 DOCS files (docs/CLI_GENERATOR_GUIDE.md, knowledge/usage.md, MARKETPLACE.md, README.md) overlapping noun-verb-cli's documentation, not a duplicate of the 45-file generator itself (package.json, gpack.toml, templates/*.tmpl, tests/, scripts/) -- correcting an imprecision, not reversing a conclusion (still correctly not-deleted either way). PATTERN NOW ESTABLISHED across 3 independent, differently-themed subdirectories (mcp-board-report/: real Erlang/Rust NIF system; cli/: real marketplace gpack; examples/archive/: real user-facing Learning Path) -- each looked like a clean grep-based deletion candidate and each turned out, on direct content inspection, to be genuine, purposeful, sometimes self-referencing content. Given 3-for-3, treating any of templates/'s remaining unexamined subdirectories (node-bindings/ -- likely the same pattern as cli/, given its own docs/archive/2025_docs/templates/node-bindings/ overlap already found in pass seven; plus lsp-max/cleanroom/ultra/papers/yawlv6/elixir-a2a/api/mcp-server/clnrm/ollama/llm_construct/ggen/ai, ~85 files combined) as presumptively-safe-pending-a-clean-grep is no longer justified -- the base rate this session has actually observed is 'probably real, verify before touching', not 'probably dead, verify before keeping'. This flips the default and is itself the terminal finding for this obligation's templates/ sub-branch: it is not a hygiene violation in the same sense the original 'orphaned' framing assumed (only clap-noun-verb-360/'s 258 files, already removed, fit that framing) -- the remaining ~206 files are correctly treated as CONTENT requiring the same product-intent judgment as examples/archive/, not further technical dead-code sweeping. Consolidating: 3 items now share one real open question -- does ggen's maintainer still want templates/mcp-board-report/, templates/cli/ (and structurally-likely templates/node-bindings/), and examples/archive/ as user-facing/marketplace-facing content (worth a re-verification pass) or consider them superseded (worth deleting)? Not resolved by this controller; named precisely, not guessed." .

Eighth pass (retrofit/ggen-self-g11) RETRACTS this obligation's own prior-pass framing of templates/mcp-board-report/ as 'zero references in the same pass... the next concrete candidate' -- that was a premature conclusion from an incomplete grep-only methodology, caught before any deletion happened (no damage, self-corrected per re-derivation discipline). Direct content inspection (not grep) found templates/mcp-board-report/ is materially different from clap-noun-verb-360/: it carries its OWN real ggen.toml manifest ('Enterprise-grade MCP+ Board Report Generation System... Erlang OTP + Rust hybrid architecture', axioms A=mu(O)/mu.mu=mu/hash(A)=hash(mu(O)) -- the SAME formula pattern this repo's own CLAUDE.md uses to describe ggen itself), and its 27 files are .tera (Tera template engine, NOT ggen's .tmpl frontmatter format) organized into coherent config/shell/rust/erlang subdirectories (gen_statem, NIFs, crypto, kill-switch, quarterly-drill, dr-drill) -- real, purposeful, thematically coherent infrastructure content, not generic combinatorial boilerplate. Being .tera not .tmpl also means build.rs's discover_templates() (which only counts ext==\"tmpl\") never counted these in its 335/77 figures at all -- a separate methodological gap from the grep-reference check. This is a self-contained ggen consumer sub-project parked inside templates/ rather than examples/, structurally similar to examples/receiptctl or examples/tcps-generated -- whether it's still wanted (needs a re-verification pass, like a receiptctl-style scaffold() test) or superseded (needs deletion) is the SAME kind of real product-intent question already correctly escalated for examples/archive/'s Learning Path, not a grep-derivable technical call. NOT deleted. cli/, node-bindings/ remain deferred from pass seven (docs/archive/2025_docs/templates/ dedup complexity). The remaining small subdirectories (lsp-max, cleanroom, ultra, papers, yawlv6, elixir-a2a, api, mcp-server, clnrm, ollama, llm_construct, ggen, ai) still unstarted -- given mcp-board-report/'s correction, each now needs the same direct-content-inspection discipline (not grep-only) before any deletion, not assumed safe from a clean grep alone.

Seventh pass (retrofit/ggen-self-g10) executed a real deletion within templates/, the largest subdirectory: templates/clap-noun-verb-360/ (258 of 491 files, 53% of the whole tree) confirmed and removed. Per-subdirectory sizing found the 491 files heavily concentrated (clap-noun-verb-360 258, cli 45, node-bindings 37, mcp-board-report 27 -- top 4 account for 75%). clap-noun-verb-360 verified safe on multiple independent grounds: every file is a homogeneous .tmpl (no mixed-in docs/config), content is generic combinatorial scaffold boilerplate (async-pattern-1..N, noun-<generic-word>-command for dozens of interchangeable nouns like adapter/alert/archive/backup/bridge/cache -- individually low-value, not curated documentation), zero real references anywhere (only the already-confirmed-dead tests/integration/template_discovery_test.rs), and no docs/archive/ counterpart exists (unlike cli/ and node-bindings/, see below). Executed: git rm -r, verified cargo check --workspace --exclude ggen-lsp clean (build.rs gracefully discovered 77 templates post-deletion, exactly 335-258, confirming the count tracks reality), just test-lib 433/433 pass. The other 3 large subdirectories (cli/, node-bindings/, mcp-board-report/) were investigated but NOT deleted -- found materially more complex than clap-noun-verb-360, deferred rather than rushed: 'cli'/'node-bindings' are severely generic words causing heavy grep false-positive collision (crates/ggen-cli, marketplace *-cli packages, docs/thesis, etc.), AND critically, docs/archive/2025_docs/templates/cli/ and docs/archive/2025_docs/templates/node-bindings/ appear to be PARALLEL, already-archived copies of overlapping content -- a third archive location this investigation had not previously mapped, raising the same dedup-not-blind-delete question LSP-ARD-PRD.md required, now at subdirectory scale. mcp-board-report/ (27 files) had zero references in the same pass but wasn't independently verified with the same rigor as clap-noun-verb-360 (content-homogeneity, docs/archive counterpart check) -- named as the next concrete candidate, not assumed safe. The remaining ~9 small subdirectories (9 files or fewer each: lsp-max, cleanroom, ultra, papers, yawlv6, elixir-a2a, api, mcp-server, clnrm, ollama, llm_construct, ggen, ai) still unstarted.

Sixth pass (retrofit/ggen-self-g9) investigated (d), examples/archive/ (1547 files, 79 subdirectories) -- found a genuine design-uncertainty boundary, not resolved this cycle by design, matching DESIGN_UNCERTAINTY_LAW's own escalation exception (materially different external business intent, not derivable from repository law/evidence). Zero real external code/config references confirmed (only Cargo.toml false-positive: a comment mentioning the differently-named examples/archive_ggen_core/, not this directory). Git-history-confirmed deliberate: commit 627f84c59 ('archive examples', PR #265) explicitly created this location as part of a real past cleanup, the same docs/archive/ pattern used elsewhere in this repo for retired-but-preserved content -- NOT scattered accidental debris like the root-level docs already removed. BUT examples/archive/README.md's own content complicates a simple 'therefore delete' conclusion: it presents itself as an active, user-facing 'Learning Path' (Beginner/Intermediate tiers) with 'Quick Start' instructions for the examples within, carrying only a staleness caveat (verification claim predates the 2026-07-17 ggen-core-replacement migration, PR #255) -- not a 'this is dead, ignore it' framing. The directory NAME signals retired; the directory's OWN CONTENT signals still-intended-as-tutorial-material. Whether ggen's documentation/onboarding strategy still wants this as a Learning Path (in which case the real defect is staleness needing a re-verification pass, not deletion) or considers it superseded scratch (in which case deletion is correct) is a genuine product-intent question this controller cannot derive from repository law or CI state alone -- the correct DESIGN_UNCERTAINTY_LAW escalation case, not a punt. Named precisely rather than guessed at either direction." .

Fifth pass (retrofit/ggen-self-g8) investigated (c), templates/ (491 files, 17+ subdirectories: llm_construct/clnrm/elixir-a2a/papers/ultra/yawlv6/mcp-server/lsp-max/cli/ggen/ai/mcp-board-report/clap-noun-verb-360/api/ollama/cleanroom/node-bindings/etc, mostly small per-directory counts) -- no deletions this pass, but the original 'orphaned, unreferenced' characterization is now precisely grounded rather than assumed, after ruling out 3 real candidate consumers, not just one grep: (1) root build.rs DOES scan templates/ at compile time and generates a `TemplateMetadata` registry into OUT_DIR/templates.rs -- initially looked load-bearing, but confirmed via full-workspace grep that NOTHING `include!`s the generated file anywhere (crates/ggen-cli's own separately-defined TemplateMetadata in conventions/planner.rs is a different, hand-written struct, not this one) -- dead output from a real build step. (2) tests/integration/template_discovery_test.rs asserts templates/ must exist with 200+ .tmpl files -- looked like real enforcement, but confirmed via `cargo test --test <name>`'s own target-not-found error (cross-checked against the full available-targets list and Cargo.toml's 21 explicit [[test]] entries, none of which reference it) that this file is NEVER COMPILED OR RUN -- Cargo's default auto-discovery only covers files directly in tests/, not nested tests/integration/*.rs, and no explicit [[test]] entry exists for it. Genuinely dead test code. (3) Several `Path::new(\"templates\")`/`.join(\"templates\")` call sites in crates/ggen-cli/src/{cmds/init.rs,conventions/*,scaffolding/*} -- confirmed these are all about the GENERIC 'templates' convention name ggen's own `init`/scaffolding commands create for OTHER (consumer) projects being initialized, not a reference to THIS repo's own root templates/ directory. All 3 hypotheses for load-bearing-ness resolved to false leads -- the original claim holds, but real investigation was required to establish that, not assumption. Deferred: given the scale (491 files) and genuine diversity (17+ apparently-unrelated one-off experiment subdirectories, largely single-digit file counts each) revealed by this pass, individually verifying deletion-safety for each subdirectory at the same rigor as the ~54 root docs already handled is disproportionate for one cycle -- named precisely for a dedicated future pass rather than bulk-deleted on the strength of the 3-hypothesis clearance alone. (d) examples/archive/ (1547 tracked files) still fully unstarted, needs its own dedicated reference-sweep." .

ctl:O-10-ci-integration-tests a ctl:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "Close CiIntegrationTestsNeverRun: fix/root-cause the 10 residual praxis-graphlaw integration-test failures and promote integration-tests to required" ;
    ctl:priority 1 ;
    ctl:state ctl:CLOSED ;
    ctl:receiptRef "retrofit/ggen-self-g4 (commit pending), PR TBD" ;
    ctl:nextAction "CLOSED 2026-07-21/22. All 10 named failures individually root-caused: 8 were test-authoring bugs (invalid GRAPH-quad CONSTRUCT-template SPARQL syntax not supported by the W3C spec itself; `effect = \"refuse\"` hooks correctly returning Err rather than the tests' assumed silent Ok rollback; a naive multi-list edge concatenation asserted globally sorted when only per-list sort is guaranteed; a receipt-hash-identity test compared receipts from two hook packs using different subject IRIs, a real hash input; 3 sh:sparql tests predating the deliberate SHACL_SPARQL_BOUNDARY=CORE_ONLY policy) and 2 were real product defects, both repaired with a pinned regression test rather than merely disclosed: (1) hooks/parsing.rs::rewrite_hook_alias silently accepted unrecognized hook: alias predicates, evading all downstream kh:-namespace-scoped validation -- now refused at the rewrite step; (2) this crate's custom SPARQL executor silently treated GRAPH <iri> {...} WHERE-clause patterns as PlanNode::Done (always zero rows) instead of matching the named graph -- now a loud, typed refusal via find_unsupported_construct, joining the existing VALUES/ORDER BY fail-closed net (retrofit:GraphLawValuesSilentZeroRows), pinned in tests/sparql_unsupported_refusal.rs. Verification: cargo test -p praxis-graphlaw --no-fail-fast 0 failures (run twice; the one apparent 3rd-run failure, datalog_conformance, was isolated and re-run clean 13/13, confirmed a transient shared-disk linker ENOSPC artifact from concurrent sessions on this machine, not a code regression); cargo check --workspace (both with and without --exclude ggen-lsp) clean; just pre-commit (11 real gates) exit 0. .github/workflows/ci.yml's integration-tests job promoted from advisory to a required dependency of ci-status in the same commit -- the false-Green risk this SPOF tracked (a real, non-empty set of integration-test failures silently never gating any PR) is now closed: the job is required and its underlying test set is genuinely green, not quarantined-green. A doc/implementation drift surfaced while root-causing the sh:sparql tests (model.rs's PROJ-407 comment claims load-time rejection; the real behavior is validation-time silent skip) was disclosed as its own new SPOF (retrofit:ShaclSparqlBoundaryDocDrift, Accepted, bounded risk) rather than fixed in this pass -- a real production shapes file (process-conformance.shacl.ttl) uses sh:sparql and this pass did not find strong enough evidence (zero found Rust consumers is not proof of zero consumers) to safely change ShapesGraph::parse's load-time behavior." ;
    ctl:verificationRequirement "cargo test -p praxis-graphlaw --no-fail-fast (0 failures, 2026-07-22); cargo check --workspace --exclude ggen-lsp and cargo check --workspace (2026-07-22, both clean); just pre-commit (2026-07-22, exit 0, 11 gates)." .

ctl:O-8 a ctl:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "composed_packs_e2e::thirty_one_packs_compose_with_verify_gates_active -- RETRACTED, false positive" ;
    ctl:priority 1 ;
    ctl:state ctl:CLOSED ;
    ctl:nextAction "RETRACTED 2026-07-21, same cycle it was opened: re-run after this cycle's cargo clean + fresh rebuild (target/debug/ggen rebuilt via cargo build -p ggen-cli-lib --bin ggen) -- the test now PASSES cleanly ('test result: ok. 1 passed'). Root cause of the original failure: a STALE cached test binary (CliHarness::cargo_bin(\"ggen\") locating an out-of-date target/debug/ggen built before some source change, not a live code defect). The original 'confirmed pre-existing via git stash' check was itself run against that same stale environment, so it wrongly corroborated a false positive rather than actually isolating anything. Correction applied per re-derivation discipline: do not let a wrong finding stand once the corrected premise (fresh binary, real pass) is in hand. [law].reflexive genuinely exists on GgenConfig::Law (crates/ggen-engine/src/config.rs:98) and this fixture's ggen.toml correctly classifies as Frontmatter and parses -- independently re-verified via two isolated repro attempts before the real re-run confirmed it." .
